	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I just reached 101 in smithing with my first character, a 14 level wood elf druid.  I didn&#8217;t start smithing until he was over 10th level.  I&#8217;d started smithing because I wanted to make studs for my tailoring skill.  Though expensive, smithing is not terribly difficult to reach 100 skill in.  I must admit, however, that I had a bit of luck.  I&#8217;d been saving animal hides for tailoring and sold all my high quality cat pelts for 5pp each, for a total of over 200pp.  I used this stash to fund my smithing skill.<BR>
<BR>
I put all the points I could into the skill.  Then I made toolboxes until they became trivial at 51.  I tried sharpening rusty weapons, but after FINALLY finding sharpening stones, I had trouble finding enough weapons to sharpen, even with my fishing skill.  So I chose toolboxes instead.  After hitting 51 I started making skewers and they took me to 101.  I plan to keep making skewers until 115.  Then I&#8217;ll start making armor to sell.  <BR>
<BR>
I only made metal bits as I needed them.  I feel to make them for skill costs too much from all the failed attempts.  By the time I started making them in bulk, I succeeded 95% of the time.  And since toolboxes only require only 1 bit and 1 water, they are a cheap and easy way to reach 51 skill.  <BR>
<BR>
I&#8217;m also working on the brewing skill so that I can make cured silk armor when my tailoring is high enough.  With all the trade skills my character is learning, including cooking, which is a hoot, perhaps I should have named my character Jack.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
